04089nam a22006015i 9780804778213DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20202011cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047782137 a10.1515/97808047782132doi  a(DE-B1597)563664  a(OCoLC)1178769010  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aJK554.E73 2011 7aPOL0400102bisacsh04a352.23/60973a352.23/609731 aEshbaugh-Soha, Matthew, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBreaking Through the Noise :bPresidential Leadership, Public Opinion, and the News Media /cMatthew Eshbaugh-Soha, Jeffrey S. Peake. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (264 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in the Modern Presidency00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1 Introduction -- t2 Presidential Leadership -- t3 Theoretical Framework and Organization -- t4 A Focused Strategy of Presidential Leadership -- t5 A Sustained Strategy of Presidential Leadership -- t6 Going Local as a Leadership Strategy -- t7 Leadership and Responsiveness in the Public Presidency -- tAppendix: Keywords Index -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aModern presidents engage in public leadership through national television addresses, routine speechmaking, and by speaking to local audiences. With these strategies, presidents tend to influence the media's agenda. In fact, presidential leadership of the news media provides an important avenue for indirect presidential leadership of the public, the president's ultimate target audience. Although frequently left out of sophisticated treatments of the public presidency, the media are directly incorporated into this book's theoretical approach and analysis. The authors find that when the public expresses real concern about an issue, such as high unemployment, the president tends to be responsive. But when the president gives attention to an issue in which the public does not have a preexisting interest, he can expect, through the news media, to directly influence public opinion. Eshbaugh-Soha and Peake offer key insights on when presidents are likely to have their greatest leadership successes and demonstrate that presidents can indeed "break through the noise" of news coverage to lead the public agenda.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aCommunication in politicszUnited States. 0aGovernment and the presszUnited States. 0aPolitical leadershipzUnited States. 0aPresidentsxPress coveragezUnited States. 0aPresidentszUnited States. 0aPress and politicszUnited States. 0aPublic opinionzUnited States. 0aPublic relations and politicszUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / American Government / Executive Branch.2bisacsh1 aPeake, Jeffrey S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080477821340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804778213423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804778213.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles